to compare 2 values we use an instruction called cmp 
it takes 2 operands and compares them and sets some flags based on the result of the comparison

it has 3 main flags
ZF - zero flag - set if the result of the comparison is zero (i.e. the two values are equal)
SF - sign flag - set if the result of the comparison is negative 
(i.e. the first value is less than the second value) BUT: its for signed comparisons only
CF - carry flag - set if there is a borrow in the comparison
(i.e. the first value is less than the second value) BUT: its for unsigned comparisons only

so based off this we can use something called a jump instruction 
basically it works like an if statement in high level languages

it checks the flags that were set by the cmp instruction and just pipes them to the jmp instruction
to handle 
different cases we have different jump instructions for each case

je - jump if equal (ZF is set)
jne - jump if not equal (ZF is not set)
jg - jump if greater (ZF is not set and SF is not set) for signed comparisons
jge - jump if greater or equal (ZF is set or SF is not set) for
    signed comparisons
jl - jump if less (SF is set) for signed comparisons
jle - jump if less or equal (ZF is set or SF is set) for signed
    comparisons

[harder ones below]:
ja - jump if above (CF is not set and ZF is not set) for unsigned
    comparisons
jae - jump if above or equal (CF is not set) for unsigned comparisons
jb - jump if below (CF is set) for unsigned comparisons
jbe - jump if below or equal (CF is set or ZF is set) for
    unsigned comparisons


